"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Deuteronomy chapters 8–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-deuteronomy-8-10-fill.py

Key decisions:
- Ch 8: v2 (40-year testing) and v3 (manna/bread) are direct NT citations (Matt 4:4); treated as direct types
- Ch 8: v15 (wilderness serpents) connects to Num 21 and John 3:14-15 — direct type
- Ch 9: vv.4-6 (not because of your righteousness) = direct type for Pauline justification
- Ch 9: v18 (Moses' 40-day intercession) = fullest Pentateuchal type of Christ's vicarious intercession
- Ch 10: v6 (Aaron dies, Eleazar succeeds) = direct Heb 7 type of permanent Melchizedekian priesthood
- Ch 10: v16 (circumcise your hearts) = direct type of new covenant Spirit-circumcision (Rom 2:29)
- Ch 10: v17 ("Lord of lords") = title given to Christ in Rev 17:14; 19:16 — direct
- Directness levels: direct (NT explicit), type, shadow, theme, revelation of God
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DEUTERONOMY = {
"8": {
"1": "<p>Carry out every commandment to live, multiply, and possess the land. Covenant obedience is the condition for the promised life. Christ is the perfectly obedient covenant-keeper who earns this life on behalf of those who could not maintain it: &quot;he learned obedience through what he suffered and, being made perfect, became the source of eternal salvation to all who obey him&quot; (Heb 5:8–9). Where Israel repeatedly failed the obedience-condition, Christ permanently satisfied it. Theme fulfilled.</p>",
"2": "<p>The forty-year wilderness journey — humbling, testing, revealing what was in Israel&apos;s heart. This forty-year period is the direct type that Matthew and Luke read as recapitulated in Jesus&apos; forty-day wilderness testing (Matt 4:1–11; Luke 4:1–13). Matthew&apos;s structure is deliberate: Israel in the wilderness for forty years; Jesus in the wilderness for forty days. Where Israel failed the test repeatedly, Jesus passed it, quoting Deuteronomy in each reply to Satan. A type with explicit NT identification.</p>",
"3": "<p>YHWH humbles Israel through hunger, then feeds them with manna — unknown food, bread from heaven — &quot;to teach you that man does not live by bread alone but by every word that comes from the mouth of the LORD.&quot; Jesus quotes this exact verse when Satan commands him to turn stones to bread (Matt 4:4; Luke 4:4), demonstrating that he lives by the Father&apos;s word, not manipulated provision. The manna is also a direct type of Christ: &quot;I am the bread of life... Your fathers ate the manna in the wilderness, and they died. This is the bread that comes down from heaven, so that one may eat of it and not die&quot; (John 6:48–50). Direct NT citation and type.</p>",
"4": "<p>&quot;Your clothing did not wear out and your feet did not swell during those forty years.&quot; YHWH&apos;s miraculous provision of material needs where human supply fails entirely. As a revelation of God&apos;s character: the Creator sustains what he calls. In Christ, this sustaining faithfulness is given eschatological scope — he who &quot;sustains all things by his powerful word&quot; (Heb 1:3) will transform the mortal body into a glorified one at the resurrection (Phil 3:21), the ultimate clothing that does not wear out (1 Cor 15:53–54). Revelation of God.</p>",
"5": "<p>&quot;Just as a man disciplines his son, so the LORD your God has been disciplining you.&quot; The father-son disciplinary relationship between YHWH and Israel. Hebrews 12:5–11 applies this father-son discipline theology directly to believers, quoting Proverbs 3:11–12: &quot;the Lord disciplines the one he loves.&quot; But it is also applied to Christ himself: &quot;although he was a Son, he learned obedience through what he suffered&quot; (Heb 5:8). The discipline pattern Israel experienced is both the type of Christ&apos;s own formation and the model for the church&apos;s sanctification. Theme.</p>",
"6": "<p>&quot;Keep the commandments of the LORD your God by walking in his ways and fearing him.&quot; The covenant call to walk in YHWH&apos;s ways. Christ walks in perfect covenant obedience (1 Pet 2:22; Heb 4:15), and through his Spirit, the righteous requirement of the law is &quot;fulfilled in us, who walk not according to the flesh but according to the Spirit&quot; (Rom 8:4). What Israel was commanded to do but could not sustain, Christ accomplishes in himself and enables in those united to him. Theme.</p>",
"7": "<p>The good land described: streams, pools, and springs flowing through valleys and hills. The well-watered, abundantly provisioned land is the concrete shape of the covenant blessing. As a shadow: the good land of Canaan anticipates the eschatological inheritance — every spiritual blessing in the heavenly places in Christ (Eph 1:3). The streams and springs of the promised land echo forward to the living water Jesus promises (John 4:14; 7:37–38) and to the river of life flowing from the throne in the new creation (Rev 22:1). Shadow.</p>",
"8": "<p>The seven species of the land — wheat, barley, vines, fig trees, pomegranates, olive oil, honey — the agricultural fullness of the promised land. The vine is significant: in John 15:1, Jesus declares &quot;I am the true vine,&quot; claiming to be the genuine source of the fruitfulness the promised land typified. The land&apos;s produce was the sign of YHWH&apos;s covenant blessing; Christ is the source from whom all true fruitfulness flows. Shadow.</p>",
"9": "<p>A land of abundance where nothing is lacking, with iron in the rocks and copper in the hills. Total material sufficiency is the sign of YHWH&apos;s covenantal provision. The NT extends this sufficiency inward: &quot;my God will supply every need of yours according to his riches in glory in Christ Jesus&quot; (Phil 4:19). What the land provided externally, Christ provides comprehensively and permanently. Theme.</p>",
"10": "<p>&quot;When you have eaten and are full, you shall bless the LORD your God for the good land he has given you.&quot; Blessing God after eating — the table grace that acknowledges all provision as gift. Jesus blesses before feeding (Mark 6:41; Matt 14:19) and at the Last Supper (Matt 26:26–27), embedding this blessing-pattern into the eucharistic meal that becomes the centerpiece of Christian worship. The meal where YHWH is blessed for the good land becomes the meal where Christ is remembered for the ultimate gift — his own body and blood. Theme.</p>",
"11": "<p>The warning not to forget YHWH by failing to keep his commandments. Covenant amnesia — forgetting God through prosperity — is the primary danger of successful settlement. The Lord&apos;s Supper is Christ&apos;s specific antidote to spiritual forgetfulness: &quot;Do this in remembrance of me&quot; (Luke 22:19; 1 Cor 11:24–25). The new covenant&apos;s memorial meal counters the Deuteronomic danger with a regular, embodied act of remembrance. Theme.</p>",
"12": "<p>The progression of prosperity: eating your fill, building fine houses, settling in. The comfortable life that makes God seem unnecessary. Jesus teaches against this danger directly in the parable of the rich fool (Luke 12:15–21) — the man who built larger barns and congratulated himself on his abundance without remembering God. The fine houses of Deut 8:12 become the larger barns of Luke 12:18. Deut 8&apos;s warning is the direct background for Jesus&apos; teaching on wealth and security. Theme.</p>",
"13": "<p>Growing herds, flocks, silver, gold — the accumulation of wealth. The danger point: when everything multiplies, God can seem to recede. This is the Deuteronomic diagnosis of the prosperous temptation that leads to forgetting. Jesus&apos; warning &quot;You cannot serve both God and money&quot; (Matt 6:24) and the parable of the sower (Matt 13:22 — &quot;the deceitfulness of wealth chokes the word&quot;) apply this Deuteronomic warning to the kingdom context. Theme.</p>",
"14": "<p>&quot;Your heart will become proud and you will forget the LORD your God who brought you out of Egypt, out of the house of slavery.&quot; Pride of heart leading to covenant amnesia — the root of all Deuteronomic apostasy. The cross is God&apos;s definitive assault on human pride: &quot;God chose what is foolish in the world to shame the wise... so that no human being might boast in the presence of God&quot; (1 Cor 1:27–29). What Deuteronomy warns against, the gospel addresses at its root. Theme.</p>",
"15": "<p>&quot;He led you through that vast and fearful wilderness with its venomous snakes and scorpions... and brought you water out of solid flint.&quot; The venomous serpents connect directly to Numbers 21:6–9, the bronze serpent episode. Jesus explicitly reads the bronze serpent as a type of himself: &quot;As Moses lifted up the serpent in the wilderness, so must the Son of Man be lifted up, that whoever believes in him may have eternal life&quot; (John 3:14–15). The wilderness of serpents from which YHWH delivers points to the cross where Christ becomes the lifted-up remedy for the serpent&apos;s bite. Direct type.</p>",
"16": "<p>&quot;He fed you with manna in the wilderness... in order to humble you and test you, so that he might do you good in the end.&quot; The goal of the wilderness testing is long-term good — the humbling is purposeful. This is the manna-type verse that frames John 6&apos;s &quot;bread of life&quot; discourse: Jesus contrasts the manna that fathers ate (and died) with himself as the bread from heaven that gives eternal life (John 6:48–51). The manna is a type not just in form (bread from heaven) but in purpose — sustaining life for those who could not sustain themselves. Type.</p>",
"17": "<p>&quot;Beware of saying to yourself, &apos;My power and the strength of my hands have produced this wealth for me.&apos;&quot; The primal temptation to self-attribution — claiming as one&apos;s own what God gave. This is the heart of Babylonian pride (Isa 47) and Pharaoh&apos;s hardness. Paul&apos;s rhetorical question answers it: &quot;What do you have that you did not receive? If then you received it, why do you boast as if you did not receive it?&quot; (1 Cor 4:7). The gospel of grace is the definitive cure for the Deut 8:17 delusion. Theme.</p>",
"18": "<p>&quot;Remember the LORD your God, for it is he who gives you the ability to produce wealth, in order to confirm his covenant that he swore to your fathers.&quot; All human capacity is given, covenant-grounded, and covenant-confirming. The wealth-producing ability is not a human achievement but a covenant gift. Paul extends this: &quot;We have this treasure in jars of clay, to show that the surpassing power belongs to God and not to us&quot; (2 Cor 4:7). In Christ, the pattern is complete — the power that produces all things comes from the one through whom all things were made (John 1:3; Col 1:16). Revelation of God.</p>",
"19": "<p>&quot;If you ever forget the LORD your God and follow other gods... you will certainly perish.&quot; The covenant curse for apostasy stated with absolute clarity: perishing is the outcome. John 3:16 is the gospel answer to this covenant threat: &quot;that whoever believes in him should not perish but have eternal life.&quot; The mōt tāmût (&quot;you will certainly perish&quot;) of Deut 8:19 is precisely the perishing John 3:16 promises to reverse. Christ absorbs the covenant death-sentence so that those in him do not perish. Direct thematic fulfillment.</p>",
"20": "<p>&quot;You will perish just like the nations the LORD is destroying before you.&quot; The nations perish for their wickedness (9:5); Israel would perish for the same covenant-breaking. Covenant death is the equal-opportunity consequence of unfaithfulness. Paul&apos;s argument in Romans 2:12–16 — that Jew and Gentile alike stand condemned before God&apos;s righteous standard — draws on this Deuteronomic principle. In Christ, both Jew and Gentile escape the perishing not through improved obedience but through the one who bore the covenant curse for both (Gal 3:13–14; Eph 2:11–16). Theme.</p>"
},
"9": {
"1": "<p>&quot;Today you are about to cross the Jordan to go in and dispossess nations greater and mightier than you.&quot; The Jordan crossing as the paradigm threshold from promise to possession. Paul reads Israel&apos;s wilderness crossings typologically in 1 Corinthians 10:1–4 — the sea-crossing and wilderness journey as types for the church&apos;s baptism and spiritual food. The Jordan crossing into rest is the type of entering the rest Christ provides (Heb 4:1–11). Theme.</p>",
"2": "<p>The Anakites — the legendary giants. &quot;Who can stand up to the Anakites?&quot; The human assessment of impossible odds. When the disciples ask &quot;Who then can be saved?&quot; at the camel-needle saying, Jesus answers: &quot;With man this is impossible, but with God all things are possible&quot; (Matt 19:25–26). The pattern — human impossibility before divine possibility — is a constant in both Testaments. The victories over what seems unconquerable are all grounded in divine power, ultimately displayed in the resurrection (Eph 1:19–20). Theme.</p>",
"3": "<p>&quot;The LORD your God is the one going ahead of you as a consuming fire.&quot; YHWH as the divine warrior who goes before. Hebrews 6:20 — &quot;Jesus has gone as a forerunner on our behalf&quot; — applies this going-before pattern to Christ. But Christ goes before not to destroy an external enemy but to face death itself: &quot;For since he himself has suffered when tempted, he is able to help those who are being tempted&quot; (Heb 2:18). The consuming fire that precedes Israel is the pattern for Christ who goes first through suffering and death to open the way for those who follow. Shadow.</p>",
"4": "<p>&quot;Do not say to yourself, &apos;The LORD has brought me in to possess this land because of my righteousness.&apos;&quot; The land is not granted on merit. This is the OT grounding for Paul&apos;s doctrine of justification by grace: &quot;we know that a person is not justified by works of the law but through faith in Jesus Christ... because by works of the law no one will be justified&quot; (Gal 2:16). The grace of the land-gift — given despite Israel&apos;s proven stubbornness — is the type of the grace of salvation given despite humanity&apos;s proven sinfulness. Direct typological connection.</p>",
"5": "<p>&quot;It is not because of your righteousness or integrity of heart that you are entering... but because of the wickedness of these nations and in order to fulfill the promise the LORD swore to your fathers.&quot; The two grounds of the gift: the nations&apos; judgment and the patriarchal promise — neither of which is Israel&apos;s merit. This is Ephesians 2:8–9 in OT form: &quot;For by grace you have been saved through faith. And this is not your own doing; it is the gift of God, not a result of works, so that no one may boast.&quot; The salvation in Christ, like the land-gift, rests entirely on divine promise and divine action. Direct type.</p>",
"6": "<p>&quot;Understand that the LORD your God is not giving you this good land to possess because of your righteousness — you are a stubborn people.&quot; The explicit denial of merit-based inheritance stated three times in three verses (vv.4, 5, 6) for emphasis. The NT&apos;s &quot;not by works&quot; has precisely this emphatic quality — Titus 3:5: &quot;not by works of righteousness that we have done, but according to his mercy he saved us.&quot; Stubborn Israel receives the land; stubborn sinners receive salvation — in both cases, the grace is real because the merit is genuinely absent. Theme.</p>",
"7": "<p>&quot;Remember... how you provoked the LORD your God to anger in the wilderness.&quot; Honest memory of failure is the precondition for understanding grace. The gospel requires this same honesty about human sinfulness: &quot;while we were still sinners, Christ died for us&quot; (Rom 5:8) carries its full weight only for those who recognize what &quot;sinners&quot; means. Deuteronomy&apos;s insistence on remembering Israel&apos;s failure is the OT school in which the gospel&apos;s diagnosis of universal sinfulness becomes credible. Theme.</p>",
"8": "<p>&quot;At Horeb you provoked the LORD to such anger that he was ready to destroy you.&quot; The golden calf incident as the paradigm case of covenantal faithlessness. Paul uses the wilderness sins as types (τύποι) of warning for the church: &quot;Now these things happened as examples [τύποι] for us, that we might not desire evil as they did&quot; (1 Cor 10:6). The Horeb rebellion prefigures the apostasy that destroys those who do not hold fast to Christ. Paul&apos;s application makes the typological status explicit. Type with direct NT identification (1 Cor 10:6–11).</p>",
"9": "<p>Moses on the mountain forty days and forty nights, eating no bread and drinking no water, to receive the covenant tablets. The forty-day fast is the prophetic fast of covenant mediation — associated with Moses (Exod 34:28), Elijah (1 Kgs 19:8), and Jesus (Matt 4:2). The pattern: forty days of total dependence and privation precede a crucial covenant moment. Jesus&apos; wilderness fast recapitulates this mediatorial privation before his public ministry begins. Type.</p>",
"10": "<p>&quot;The tablets of stone, written by the finger of God.&quot; The finger of God writes the covenant law at Sinai. In Luke 11:20, Jesus says &quot;if it is by the finger of God that I cast out demons, then the kingdom of God has come upon you&quot; — the same finger of God that wrote the law in stone now acts through the Son&apos;s ministry. The power that inscribed the covenant is the power that expels the powers of darkness. Theme.</p>",
"11": "<p>The covenant tablets given to Moses after forty days — the mediator receives the covenant document for the people. Moses as covenant mediator is the OT template. Christ is the mediator of a better covenant (Heb 8:6; 9:15; 12:24), enacted not on stone tablets but through his own blood. The tablets Moses received were breakable (v.17); the new covenant Christ mediates is not dependent on human faithfulness but on his own. Shadow.</p>",
"12": "<p>YHWH tells Moses the people have already turned to a cast idol. The law violated while still being given — the simultaneous reception and transgression of the covenant. This moment demonstrates the law&apos;s fundamental limitation: it can reveal and command but cannot change the heart that receives it. Paul&apos;s analysis in Romans 7 — &quot;the very commandment that promised life proved to be death to me&quot; — is the theological articulation of this Horeb moment. The new covenant addresses what the Sinai tablets could not accomplish (2 Cor 3:3–6). Theme.</p>",
"13": "<p>&quot;I have observed this people, and they are indeed a stubborn people.&quot; The divine assessment of Israel&apos;s intractable stubbornness — not an occasional lapse but a settled condition. This is the OT&apos;s clearest statement of the human heart&apos;s resistance to God apart from transformation. The prophet Ezekiel will receive the diagnosis with a promise: &quot;I will remove the heart of stone from your flesh and give you a heart of flesh&quot; (Ezek 36:26). In Christ and through his Spirit, this promise is enacted. Revelation of God leading to prophetic type.</p>",
"14": "<p>YHWH offers to destroy Israel and make a mightier nation from Moses alone. The covenant could theoretically restart — YHWH&apos;s purpose would not ultimately fail even if this generation perished. But Moses&apos; intercession prevents this. The pattern — sinful people threatened with destruction, mediator intercedes, destruction averted — is the fullest OT template for Christ&apos;s work: &quot;He always lives to make intercession for them&quot; (Heb 7:25). Type.</p>",
"15": "<p>Moses descends from the blazing mountain with the covenant tablets. The fire of God&apos;s presence continues while Moses carries the covenant document to the guilty people. The holiness of God and the mercy toward sinners exist simultaneously — not contradicting but building toward the cross where they meet: &quot;Righteousness and peace have kissed each other&quot; (Ps 85:10). Christ is the place where divine holiness is satisfied and sinners are reconciled. Revelation of God.</p>",
"16": "<p>Moses sees the golden calf — the covenant is already broken. The mediator sees his people&apos;s sin. Christ as the great High Priest &quot;can sympathize with our weaknesses&quot; (Heb 4:15) — not ignorant of human sin but acquainted with it from within. The seeing of sin by the mediator is not the end of the story but the beginning of intercession. Theme.</p>",
"17": "<p>Moses smashes the tablets before Israel&apos;s eyes — a dramatic enactment of the broken covenant. The covenant shattered by human sin is not the final word. The tablets are rewritten (ch. 10), and beyond that, the covenant itself is renewed in a form that cannot be shattered: &quot;For if that first covenant had been faultless, there would have been no occasion to look for a second&quot; (Heb 8:7). The broken tablets point forward to the unbreakable new covenant ratified by Christ&apos;s blood. Shadow.</p>",
"18": "<p>Moses prostrates himself before YHWH for forty days and forty nights, fasting completely, interceding for the people who sinned against their covenant God. This is the most extended type of vicarious intercession in the Pentateuch. Moses&apos; total self-abnegation on behalf of the guilty people — forty days of complete deprivation — prefigures Christ who &quot;emptied himself, by taking the form of a servant&quot; (Phil 2:7) and who &quot;in the days of his flesh... offered up prayers and supplications, with loud cries and tears&quot; (Heb 5:7). The fullest OT type of intercession. Type.</p>",
"19": "<p>&quot;I was terrified of the LORD&apos;s fierce anger against you, which was about to destroy you. But the LORD listened to me.&quot; Moses&apos; intercession turns away divine wrath. This is the type whose substance is Christ&apos;s propitiatory death: &quot;He is the propitiation for our sins&quot; (1 John 2:2). Moses interceded and YHWH relented; Christ bore the wrath and the wrath was exhausted. The type is intercession that averts; the fulfillment is the sacrifice that absorbs. Direct type with explicit NT fulfillment.</p>",
"20": "<p>Moses intercedes specifically for Aaron — the most directly guilty party, the one who made the calf. The scope of Moses&apos; intercession extends to the leader of the apostasy. Christ&apos;s intercession is similarly comprehensive: &quot;He always lives to make intercession for them&quot; (Heb 7:25), with no qualifier on the severity of the sin. &quot;The blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin&quot; (1 John 1:7) — the &quot;all&quot; covers even the golden-calf-makers. Type.</p>",
"21": "<p>Moses burns the calf, grinds it to dust, throws it in the stream — total elimination of the idol. Not preserved as a warning but completely destroyed. Christ&apos;s death destroys the works of the devil (1 John 3:8): &quot;He disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him&quot; (Col 2:15). The idol that seduced Israel is ground to dust; the powers that enslaved humanity are disarmed. The destruction is the pattern of Christ&apos;s victory. Theme.</p>",
"22": "<p>The repeated provocations: Taberah (fire), Massah (testing the water), Kibroth-hattaavah (craving meat). The pattern of rebellion is pervasive, not isolated. Paul cites the Taberah and Kibroth incidents in 1 Cor 10:6–10 as &quot;examples for us&quot; (τύποι) — the repeated wilderness sins function as types warning the church against the same patterns: idolatry, testing Christ, grumbling. The types work precisely because the sin-patterns recur in every generation. Type with direct NT identification.</p>",
"23": "<p>&quot;You rebelled against the LORD your God&apos;s command. You did not trust him and refused to obey him.&quot; The Kadesh-barnea refusal — the failure to trust YHWH&apos;s power to deliver the land. Hebrews 3:15–19 reads this episode as the paradigm warning for the church: the wilderness generation failed to enter God&apos;s rest because of unbelief. The same rest is available to believers who hold fast to the faith; the same failure of trust is the danger. Direct typological application in Hebrews 3–4.</p>",
"24": "<p>&quot;You have been rebellious against the LORD from the day I first knew you.&quot; Pervasive, congenital rebellion — not occasional but from the beginning. This is the OT articulation of what Paul diagnoses as the universal human condition: &quot;all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God&quot; (Rom 3:23); &quot;None is righteous, no, not one&quot; (Rom 3:10). The recognition of total, persistent rebellion is what makes the gospel&apos;s grace credible — it rescues not the slightly imperfect but the thoroughly rebellious. Theme.</p>",
"25": "<p>Moses prostrates himself again for forty days and nights because YHWH threatened to destroy the people. The second extended intercession. Moses&apos; persistent intercession — two separate forty-day periods of prostration and fasting — reveals the costliness of mediation. Christ&apos;s intercession is costly to the point of death: &quot;For this reason he had to be made like them, fully human in every way, in order that he might become a merciful and faithful high priest... and that he might make atonement for the sins of the people&quot; (Heb 2:17). Type.</p>",
"26": "<p>Moses prays: &quot;Do not destroy your people and your inheritance, whom you redeemed by your greatness and brought out of Egypt with a mighty hand.&quot; Moses appeals to YHWH&apos;s redemptive investment — the Exodus — as the ground for mercy. The logic: you have already redeemed them; to destroy them now would be to undo your own work. Christ&apos;s intercession makes the same appeal: the Father&apos;s investment in the Son&apos;s atoning work becomes the ground of the believers&apos; perseverance (John 17:24; Rom 8:31–34 — &quot;He who did not spare his own Son... who shall bring any charge against God&apos;s elect?&quot;). Type.</p>",
"27": "<p>&quot;Remember your servants Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.&quot; Moses appeals to the Abrahamic covenant — unconditional, sworn with an oath — as the reason not to destroy this generation. Paul similarly argues that God&apos;s promises to Abraham cannot be annulled by Israel&apos;s unfaithfulness (Rom 11:1–5, 25–29). The bedrock of divine faithfulness to the Abrahamic covenant is what grounds both Moses&apos; intercession and Paul&apos;s confidence in God&apos;s ultimate purpose for Israel. In Christ, this faithfulness reaches its yes: &quot;all the promises of God find their Yes in him&quot; (2 Cor 1:20). Theme.</p>",
"28": "<p>&quot;Otherwise the land you brought us from will say, &apos;The LORD was unable to bring them to the land he had promised.&apos;&quot; Moses appeals to YHWH&apos;s reputation among the nations. The nations&apos; potential misreading of Israel&apos;s fate — that YHWH failed or hated them — must not be allowed. The vindication of God&apos;s name is a motive throughout the prophets (Ezek 36:22: &quot;I am going to do this... not for your sake... but for the sake of my holy name&quot;). In Christ, God&apos;s name is vindicated definitively: the resurrection answers every charge that God failed his covenant (Rom 3:3–4, 25–26). Revelation of God.</p>",
"29": "<p>&quot;But they are your people and your inheritance, whom you brought out by your great power and your outstretched arm.&quot; The people are YHWH&apos;s possession — his naḥălâ, his inheritance. The NT describes believers as God&apos;s own possession: &quot;you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a people for his own possession&quot; (1 Pet 2:9, using the sĕgullâ vocabulary of Deut 7:6; 14:2; 26:18). What Moses asserts of Israel as the ground of intercession — they are yours — is what the church inherits through Christ. Theme.</p>"
},
"10": {
"1": "<p>YHWH commands Moses to chisel new tablets and make a wooden chest — the covenant is renewed and housed. The ark as the container of the renewed covenant is a type of Christ as the dwelling of God with his people. Paul uses the ark&apos;s mercy seat (kapporeth) directly in Romans 3:25: &quot;God presented Christ as a hilastērion [mercy seat/propitiation] through faith in his blood.&quot; The place where covenant and atonement meet — the ark&apos;s lid where blood was sprinkled on the Day of Atonement — is the type Paul applies to the cross. Direct type (Rom 3:25).</p>",
"2": "<p>&quot;I will write on the tablets the words that were on the first tablets, which you broke.&quot; The broken covenant is renewed without alteration — the same words, the same demands. God&apos;s covenant standard does not lower after Israel&apos;s failure; it is re-established. The new covenant similarly does not lower the moral standard but provides what the old covenant could not: the Spirit who writes the law on the heart (Jer 31:33; 2 Cor 3:3). The renewal of the tablets is the shadow; the Spirit-written heart is the fulfillment. Shadow.</p>",
"3": "<p>Moses makes the ark of acacia wood — the incorruptible desert timber used throughout the tabernacle. The ark of incorruptible wood houses the covenant word. As a shadow: Christ&apos;s body does not see corruption (Acts 2:27, 31 — Peter cites Ps 16:10 of the resurrection: &quot;you will not let your Holy One see corruption&quot;). The incorruptible material of the ark points forward to the incorruptible one who permanently houses God&apos;s presence. Shadow.</p>",
"4": "<p>YHWH writes the same Ten Commandments on the new tablets — the covenant faithfully re-established. God&apos;s word stands despite human breaking; his covenant purposes do not collapse under the weight of Israel&apos;s failure. The resurrection is the NT parallel: what seemed destroyed on Good Friday is fully restored and confirmed on Easter morning. &quot;All the promises of God find their Yes in him&quot; (2 Cor 1:20). Revelation of God.</p>",
"5": "<p>The tablets are placed in the ark, where they remain. The covenant document housed in the covenant container — the word of God at the heart of Israel&apos;s life and worship. Christ as the Word made flesh (John 1:14) is the fulfillment: the covenant word is no longer in a chest carried through the wilderness but incarnate in a person who tabernacled among us. The ark that housed the stone tablets is the shadow; the person of Christ is the substance. Shadow.</p>",
"6": "<p>Aaron dies at Moserah and Eleazar his son takes over the priestly ministry. The death of the high priest requiring succession. Hebrews 7:23–25 makes the contrast with Christ explicit: &quot;The former priests were many in number, because they were prevented by death from continuing in office, but he holds his priesthood permanently, because he continues forever. Consequently, he is able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him, since he always lives to make intercession for them.&quot; Aaron&apos;s death and succession is the type whose weakness reveals the need for an indestructible priest. Direct type (Heb 7).</p>",
"7": "<p>The journey from Gudgodah to Jotbathah, a land of flowing streams. A transitional travel note. Even in movement through wilderness stages, YHWH accompanies his people to better ground. The promise of the streams — the flowing water in the desert — echoes Isaiah 35:6–7 and 41:18 (streams in the desert as eschatological renewal). In Christ: &quot;Whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again&quot; (John 4:14). The journey toward flowing streams is the type; Christ as the source of living water is the fulfillment. Theme.</p>",
"8": "<p>The LORD sets apart Levi to carry the ark, stand before the LORD, minister to him, and pronounce blessings in his name — the three dimensions of Levitical calling. These three are fulfilled and transcended in Christ: he carries (and is) God&apos;s covenant presence, he is the eternal priest who ministers before the Father in the heavenly sanctuary (Heb 8:1–2), and through him all blessing flows to the nations (Gal 3:14; Eph 1:3). The Levitical calling is the shadow; Christ&apos;s priesthood is the substance. Type.</p>",
"9": "<p>&quot;The LORD himself is his inheritance.&quot; Levi receives no land allotment — YHWH himself is Levi&apos;s portion. This is the highest inheritance formula in the OT, echoing Numbers 18:20 (Aaron: &quot;I am your portion and your inheritance among the Israelites&quot;) and Psalm 16:5 (&quot;LORD, you are my portion and my cup&quot;). In Christ, this inheritance is extended to every believer: &quot;the riches of his glorious inheritance in the saints&quot; (Eph 1:18); &quot;God himself will be with them&quot; (Rev 21:3). God-as-inheritance moves from the priestly tribe to the entire people of God. Shadow.</p>",
"10": "<p>Moses&apos; second forty days on the mountain; YHWH listens again and is unwilling to destroy. The persistence of divine mercy — the same grace extended twice after the same rebellion. &quot;Where sin increased, grace abounded all the more&quot; (Rom 5:20). YHWH&apos;s repeated mercy toward the stubborn is not weakness but the character that reaches its definitive expression in the cross: &quot;God demonstrates his own love for us in this: while we were still sinners, Christ died for us&quot; (Rom 5:8). Revelation of God.</p>",
"11": "<p>&quot;Get up and lead the people on their journey so that they may go in and take possession of the land.&quot; The resumption of the covenant mission after discipline and restoration. The pattern of failure, intercession, renewal, and resumed mission is the structure of both the OT covenant and the believer&apos;s life in Christ. The risen Christ resumes his disciples after their failures: &quot;Go therefore and make disciples of all nations&quot; (Matt 28:19). The mission continues through the Mediator&apos;s restoration. Theme.</p>",
"12": "<p>&quot;What does the LORD your God ask of you except to fear the LORD your God, to walk in all his ways, to love him, and to serve the LORD your God with all your heart and with all your soul.&quot; The summary of the covenant demand — the practical content of the Shema. Jesus quotes the love-command from Deuteronomy 6:5 and Leviticus 19:18 as the two greatest commandments (Matt 22:37–40), building directly on this verse. Christ himself embodies this summary perfectly — the one who fears God (Heb 5:7), walks in God&apos;s ways without stumbling (1 Pet 2:22), loves God utterly (John 14:31), and serves God to the point of death (Phil 2:8). The covenant demand Christ fulfills and, through the Spirit, enables in his people (Rom 8:4). Direct connection.</p>",
"13": "<p>&quot;Keep the LORD&apos;s commandments and statutes that I am commanding you today for your own good.&quot; The commandments are for Israel&apos;s benefit — the Creator&apos;s design for creaturely flourishing, not arbitrary imposition. Jesus&apos; &quot;I came that they may have life and have it abundantly&quot; (John 10:10) continues this connection between God&apos;s word and fullness of life. The law&apos;s purpose is always the good of those who receive it; Christ is the fulfillment of that purpose. Theme.</p>",
"14": "<p>&quot;To the LORD your God belong the heavens, even the highest heavens, the earth and everything in it.&quot; The cosmic ownership declaration — the entire creation belongs to YHWH. Paul cites this principle (from Ps 24:1) in 1 Cor 10:26: &quot;the earth is the Lord&apos;s, and everything in it.&quot; In Christ, this cosmic lordship is exercised through the one to whom &quot;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given&quot; (Matt 28:18) and through whom all things were created (Col 1:16). The Creator&apos;s ownership is expressed through the Son&apos;s universal lordship. Revelation of God.</p>",
"15": "<p>&quot;Yet the LORD delighted in your fathers and loved them, and he chose you, their descendants, above all peoples.&quot; Election by delight and love — the basis is YHWH&apos;s sovereign affection, not Israel&apos;s merit or size. Ephesians 1:4–5: &quot;In love he predestined us for adoption to himself as sons through Jesus Christ, according to the purpose of his will.&quot; The election of Israel in the patriarchs is the OT type; the election of the church in Christ is the fulfillment. Both rest on the same foundation: divine delight and choice, not human achievement. Revelation of God.</p>",
"16": "<p>&quot;So circumcise your hearts and stop being stubborn.&quot; The call to inner transformation — the law commands what only God can accomplish. Deuteronomy anticipates its own unfulfillment here: the stubborn people are told to un-stubborn themselves, which they cannot do. Jeremiah 4:4 repeats the call; Ezekiel 36:26 promises what it demands (&quot;I will remove the heart of stone&quot;); Romans 2:29 calls it &quot;circumcision of the heart, by the Spirit, not by the letter.&quot; In Christ, the Spirit effects the inner transformation the law could only command. Direct type fulfilled in Christ through the Spirit.</p>",
"17": "<p>&quot;For the LORD your God is God of gods and Lord of lords — the great, mighty, and awesome God.&quot; The title &quot;Lord of lords&quot; (ʾădōnê hāʾădōnîm) belongs to YHWH alone in the OT. In Revelation 17:14 and 19:16, this title is applied to Jesus Christ: &quot;he is Lord of lords and King of kings.&quot; The title that Deuteronomy declares belongs to the incomparable God of Israel is given to the crucified and risen Jesus, identifying him with YHWH in the strongest terms available. Direct NT connection (Rev 17:14; 19:16).</p>",
"18": "<p>&quot;He upholds justice for the fatherless and the widow, and loves the foreigner, providing them with food and clothing.&quot; YHWH&apos;s character as the defender and provider for the most vulnerable. This is the ethical character of God that Jesus enacts in his ministry — feeding the hungry, welcoming the outsider, defending the powerless — and that he presents as the basis of final judgment in Matthew 25:31–46 (&quot;I was hungry and you gave me food... I was a stranger and you welcomed me&quot;). The God who cares for the fatherless and foreigner meets humanity in the face of those who need his care. Revelation of God enacted in Christ.</p>",
"19": "<p>&quot;So love the foreigner, for you were foreigners in the land of Egypt.&quot; Compassion grounded in memory of one&apos;s own alienation. Paul applies this exact logic to the Gentiles&apos; inclusion in Christ: &quot;remember that at that time you were without Christ, excluded from citizenship in Israel... But now in Christ Jesus you who once were far away have been brought near by the blood of Christ&quot; (Eph 2:11–13). The foreigners who love foreigners because they were once foreign themselves is the OT prototype; the formerly excluded Gentiles who welcome the excluded is the NT fulfillment. Direct conceptual connection (Eph 2).</p>",
"20": "<p>&quot;Fear the LORD your God. Serve him, hold fast to him, and take oaths in his name.&quot; &quot;Hold fast&quot; (dāḇaq) is the language of covenantal adhesion — the same word used for the survivors of Baal Peor (4:4). In Christ, this holding fast is enabled by union rather than command alone: &quot;Abide in me, and I in you&quot; (John 15:4). What Deuteronomy commands as an act of the will, Christ establishes as a relationship of mutual indwelling. The command to cling is fulfilled in the vine-and-branches union. Theme.</p>",
"21": "<p>&quot;He is your praise and he is your God — the one who has done these great and awe-inspiring things for you.&quot; YHWH as the content of Israel&apos;s praise — not merely the recipient of praise but himself the substance praised. Hebrews 2:12 applies Psalm 22:22 to Christ: &quot;I will tell of your name to my brothers; in the midst of the congregation I will sing your praise.&quot; The crucified and risen Christ sings the praise of God in the assembly of his people — the one who is God&apos;s praise-object becomes, through the Son, the one who leads the praise. Theme.</p>",
"22": "<p>&quot;Your fathers went down to Egypt as seventy people, and now the LORD your God has made you as numerous as the stars of the sky.&quot; The Abrahamic promise of star-like multiplication (Gen 15:5) fulfilled in the Exodus generation. The promise kept is the ground of confidence for greater promises. In Christ, the children of Abraham are extended beyond ethnic Israel to all who share Abraham&apos;s faith: &quot;he is the father of us all&quot; (Rom 4:16), and the final gathering encompasses &quot;every nation, tribe, people and language&quot; (Rev 7:9) — a multitude that fulfills what the stars of the sky only shadowed. Theme.</p>"
}
}

